WEBVTT

00:08.840 --> 00:14.767
Can you tell me about your early life, where and 
when you were born, your family, that sort of

00:08.840 --> 00:14.767
thing? I was born April 28, 1916, in Sutton County, 
Texas. Sonora is a county seat. My parents lived on

00:25.040 --> 00:26.762
a ranch. And so my early years were spent there. 
What was your ranch's name? What? What was the

00:34.652 --> 00:35.793
ranch's name? The ranch? Well, my father was W.W. 
Williamson, and we didn't have a name for the

00:37.392 --> 00:42.218
ranch. But he ranched there for about 35 years. Do 
you have any brothers and sisters? Yes. I have one

00:49.847 --> 00:52.029
sister and three brothers.

00:55.093 --> 00:59.098
Can you tell me about your education and the jobs 
you've held?

01:02.722 --> 01:06.927
Actually, I started the school in Sonora. And at 
that time, I guess the age to start was six years

01:07.902 --> 01:14.197
old. But we were the closest house to the school. My 
mother became a great friend of the first grade

01:18.588 --> 01:21.355
teacher. And I was the only one at home. So the 
teacher would tell my mother what she was doing

01:25.264 --> 01:32.714
with the class at school and let her have the books 
and all. So my mother had been a teacher, so she

01:32.774 --> 01:35.557
taught me. So that's how I got such an early start at 
age five. And when I was six at the end of April, she

01:39.102 --> 01:46.271
told my mother to let me come on to school that I was 
six then. So I really was in school. less than a

01:50.073 --> 01:52.055
year, but she promoted me. And so, my mother talked 
with the superintendent to see if I should start

01:53.236 --> 02:05.409
back through the first grade, but he said it wasn't 
important that I could handle the work, so I just

01:53.236 --> 02:05.409
went on from there. So that made me graduate early, 
and graduate early from college. I've been 16 less

02:12.095 --> 02:18.662
than a month, and I graduated from high school. 20 
less a month when I graduated from college. And

02:25.324 --> 02:27.726
I've been about it during high school. I don't 
know.

02:42.580 --> 02:48.565
We moved from the ranch in Sutton County in, I 
guess, 1928.

02:51.582 --> 03:16.408
and uh my mother yeah my mother had um maintained 
two homes while we were in school in sonora i

02:51.582 --> 03:16.408
finished the seventh grade there and uh she 
decided that she was just not gonna do that anymore

02:51.582 --> 03:16.408
she never learned to drive so she couldn't drive in 
this school so uh who moves the ranch in our county.

03:19.525 --> 03:22.728
I was in eighth grade when I was 12. And there's a big 
question about how was I going to get to school,

03:22.748 --> 03:27.853
because there weren't any school buses yet. So I 
said, well, I'd love to ride a horse, so I'll just

03:27.873 --> 03:31.437
ride. My dad said, well, I want you to understand, 
if you say you're going to ride, you're going to

03:31.557 --> 03:36.862
ride rain or shine. And he meant it. And they got me 
this rain slipper that buckled around each leg.

03:44.369 --> 03:46.952
And I rode seven miles to school. seven miles back, 
14 mile run trip. Quite an experience. Kind of lost

03:51.211 --> 03:54.195
my love of horseback riding. How long did it take? 
As I remember, it was about 30 minutes. But my

04:00.183 --> 04:05.310
mother was always afraid I was going to kill the 
horse because I ran it all the way both ways.

04:08.575 --> 04:11.559
And it was quite an experience if it was cold and 
icy. Winters were colder back then. And Anyway, I

04:16.514 --> 04:17.655
survived. Don't think I was even sick that year. 
Did he ever, like, throw you or give you trouble?

04:24.102 --> 04:28.747
The first day I rode to school, he'd never been 
around that many people. I don't know, it's not

04:29.047 --> 04:32.031
read straight up, but I stayed on. And his worst 
habit was, I guess his worst, when there was a

04:33.212 --> 04:38.778
thunderstorm. Of course, I had to hitch him to a 
tree, and he whined around the tree. pull his head

04:43.615 --> 04:46.059
back and break the bridle and take off. So I used to 
have to hunt him all the time after a storm. And he

04:52.007 --> 04:56.414
had a bad habit of, he got excited, he'd run away 
with me. But anyway, as I say, I survived it and that

04:57.495 --> 05:03.604
was the only year that I had the right. Next year, my 
sister taught that school because she graduated

05:04.125 --> 05:08.712
from college and The fellow she was to marry had one 
more year in Texas. And so she taught that school

05:14.693 --> 05:19.578
and of course she drove us. You don't know about the 
next year when I was 14.

05:26.526 --> 05:30.590
My parents bought me a little green Ford Sport 
Roadster with a rumble seat. And I drove 23 miles

05:31.811 --> 05:35.155
into school in Menard. over dirt roads, which 
meant if it rained I'd get stuck sometimes. And

05:41.921 --> 05:48.670
they tell me that I drove a little speedy because I 
wanted to get there to play tennis before school

05:41.921 --> 05:48.670
started. And I played late in the afternoon after 
school was out. My mother always insisted I get

05:52.675 --> 05:54.898
home by dark. So that was my junior year. What else 
do we need to know? Do you have any curfews? Any

06:03.834 --> 06:04.255
what? Curfews. Besides, you know, being home by 
dark. Oh. Well. It kind of drove my mother crazy

06:10.121 --> 06:18.110
because there was always some event I needed to be 
there for in the evenings. And so she finally

06:19.431 --> 06:25.718
decided that my senior year she would let us have an 
apartment in this little town. So I wouldn't be on

06:26.960 --> 06:29.222
the road at all times if not.

06:33.168 --> 06:40.079
Then

06:33.168 --> 06:40.079
you went on to the University of Texas? Yeah. You 
know, this is just a small school. I think there

06:46.670 --> 06:48.493
were 36 in my class. And you were valedictorian? I 
was valedictorian. My mother had been a teacher,

06:54.906 --> 06:59.911
and it just sort of ran in the family of my oldest 
sister. My oldest sister, actually. She was

07:03.154 --> 07:04.095
valedictorian. And then my next brother was 
salutatorian. My mother was very disappointed in

07:07.639 --> 07:09.220
him. The next brother was valedictorian. He 
graduated the day he was 16. And unfortunately, he

07:16.087 --> 07:19.731
died one week before he was to go to college. He was 
around four years older than I. That's something

07:22.223 --> 07:35.359
that nobody would die of now, because he'd been 
hurt going to help a neighbor fight a

07:22.223 --> 07:35.359
fire. And then you went on to college when you were 
16? Yeah, but see, we didn't have any counselors or

07:37.362 --> 07:42.188
anything. This is a very small school. Anyway, I 
guess I should have, my husband would have said I

07:44.633 --> 07:50.141
should have majored in home ed because I didn't 
have a lot of those skills. But instead of that, I

07:51.023 --> 07:53.747
picked something less practical. Anyway, so I go 
to the University of Texas. Freshman, 16 years

07:59.415 --> 08:01.118
old. Stayed in Little Field on. And the 
interesting thing about that that I learned many,

08:04.723 --> 08:09.831
many years later George Littlefield was one of the 
biggest benefactors of the University of Texas.

08:15.328 --> 08:17.329
Of course, I didn't just live in Littlefield Dorm. 
It didn't mean much to me. Walked past Littlefield

08:18.731 --> 08:21.754
Home on the way to campus.

08:24.556 --> 08:28.560
The statues that are on the campus there were put 
there with Littlefield money. The big fountain

08:29.180 --> 08:32.744
with the bronze horses. It's Littlefield 
Fountain. Found out many years later that at one

08:35.426 --> 08:39.430
time, he owned a ranch that I grew up on. uh, in an 
abstract which I didn't realize that had a copy of

08:41.047 --> 08:53.355
George Littlefield's will in one of the abstracts 
of the rank. But anyway, uh, What do you know about

08:56.453 --> 08:58.496
school women? So you went to UT in 1938? No, I went 
there in 1932. Were there a lot of women there

09:04.083 --> 09:08.449
during that time? Oh, there wasn't any total 
enrollment. As I remember it, it was about 6,500

09:12.595 --> 09:19.384
when I went there. And when I graduated, I think 
there were about 2,000 more. So, like A&M, you

09:23.981 --> 09:31.754
know, it had just grown beyond everybody's 
expectations. And I think it's quite different

09:32.916 --> 09:35.901
than what it is now. If we had a date or anything, we 
had to sign out and had to sign in. We had strict

09:41.330 --> 09:43.453
hours and Anyway, at the end of that freshman year, 
I was elected back on the upper class council. They

09:49.445 --> 09:59.545
were elected back about 12 girls, two, sort of like 
the RAs now, I suppose, the bachelors, the

09:49.445 --> 09:59.545
freshmen. And

09:59.706 --> 10:05.357
I stayed there that year. I was president of Dawn. I 
don't know why, but somebody stuck me with that.

10:13.261 --> 10:19.089
And then I was elected back again, so I stayed in the 
freshman girls' dorm for three years. And then my

10:19.650 --> 10:24.297
last year, my senior year, I stayed in Charlotte. 
And you graduated in 1936? I graduated in 36. You

10:27.361 --> 10:28.122
were a 20? I've been 20 less than a month. So, you 
know, it was not to my advantage to graduate that

10:31.268 --> 10:42.768
young because it was kind of hard to get a job 
teaching, which I did one whole year. Um, you said,

10:45.093 --> 10:50.262
we're going to get to teaching in a minute. I had 
various activities, I don't know what all, but I

10:51.035 --> 10:56.180
served on student government two years. It was 
called Student Assembly over there. From the

10:59.843 --> 11:03.086
College of Education, or School of Education, 
whichever it was. You said your husband said you

11:04.647 --> 11:07.110
should have taken homemaking. Why do you say that? 
Oh, yes, yes. Why do you say that? Because I

11:12.214 --> 11:13.756
couldn't cook. And he was from a family of boys, and 
his mother had been a real good cook. And... We're

11:21.680 --> 11:23.122
getting ahead of ourselves. Actually, I don't 
remember ever being introduced to Earl Rudder. My

11:30.870 --> 11:39.739
older brother, so there's six years difference in 
our ages, and my older brother had been at Tarleton

11:30.870 --> 11:39.739
when Earl was. And I sort of had my eye on him from 
looking at the angles. It was strange. In fact, I

11:47.009 --> 11:51.904
was no more than maybe 11 years old when I took note 
of him. And he was a big football player, the

11:52.486 --> 11:57.762
captain and all that. This little town, Minari. 
And see, I lived 23 miles from there. But they had a

12:05.321 --> 12:08.866
hotel that had the whole top floor was ballroom. It 
had the best dances. And that's where I first met

12:12.291 --> 12:14.434
her. We started dancing together. I was my 
brother's sister. I knew who he was. And right

12:22.865 --> 12:26.711
after college, you taught for one year? I got the 
job. He came down. my senior year, earlier. We'd

12:30.947 --> 12:33.734
been dating for a couple years already. Only when 
he was, when I was home from school. And so he came

12:37.323 --> 12:41.494
down and said I would apply in Brady. All my friends 
went to Houston to preach, but I got the job in

12:41.514 --> 12:46.767
Brady. And I taught one year, and that was 
depression. And they had a rule that they wouldn't

12:50.295 --> 12:56.123
hire a married teacher. Of course, I made the 
fantastic sum of $900 for the entire year. $100 a

13:01.510 --> 13:05.236
month, and you taught nine months, and that's all 
you got paid. And I was so young, and I guess full of

13:06.457 --> 13:13.487
pep, that I was sponsored for everything they had. 
I was sponsored by the ball club, and I never... I

13:15.873 --> 13:17.276
played a game. That was before school, 7.30 in the 
morning. And then I sponsored the cap squad after

13:19.461 --> 13:21.586
school. And then I sponsored senior class. So it 
was kind of a busy year. And anyway, We waited until

13:31.398 --> 13:36.946
I was re-elected for another year before letting 
the board know that we planned to get married. And

13:38.469 --> 13:43.857
Earl told them that I would be glad to teach if they 
saw fit to change the rules. But they didn't change

13:44.258 --> 13:45.219
it. They just let me be the chief substitute. And it 
wouldn't matter a whole lot because we were just

13:48.384 --> 13:52.410
there one more year. And then he was made football 
coach. See he was a football coach when I married

13:55.755 --> 13:57.277
him. He was made football coach at Tarleton. So 
that was 1938. So we go to Tarleton and as I told him

14:04.448 --> 14:14.263
last fall when he was named Distinguished Alumnus 
up there, the first one they had named

14:04.448 --> 14:14.263
posthumously. in my remarks i told him that he was 
doubly glad to get that job because in the first

14:14.817 --> 14:39.964
place he made 30 a month more than he'd made 
coaching in high school and the next reason was he

14:14.817 --> 14:39.964
could put me in back in school and have cook which he 
did did he really oh yeah of course he thought i was

14:14.817 --> 14:39.964
sorry strange because i had grown up on a ranch and 
did not have a milk with cow dress of chicken But

14:40.366 --> 14:43.069
cooking, he just couldn't forgive that. And I 
think the last straw was when he told me once that he

14:43.650 --> 14:51.941
thought because I'd grown up on the ranch that I 
surely know how to cook a pot of red beans. So he told

14:51.961 --> 14:56.046
me that day, he said, I'm so hungry for a good pot of 
red beans. And I thought, OK. So I went to the

14:57.528 --> 15:01.152
grocery store and bought five pounds, came home, 
and put them all on the cook. And they just had to do

15:01.813 --> 15:03.455
everything in my kitchen. So with that, he decided 
he better let me have some fame in hometown. So I

15:09.526 --> 15:12.151
guess it's helped a lot. Where'd you get your 
training at? That was at Tarleton's. He was

15:14.816 --> 15:16.158
football coach there. So he just put me in school.

15:20.246 --> 15:21.288
And he was from Brady? He was born in Brady? No, he 
was born in Eden, which is... very small it's a one

15:26.603 --> 15:55.294
traffic light crown to this day and that's where he 
was born there are two pictures in the high school

15:26.603 --> 15:55.294
in eden one is a general ira acre he was head of the uh 
all our air forces in european theater and in

15:26.603 --> 15:55.294
earl's picture so i guess they're still there i 
haven't been there in a long time but the last time i

15:26.603 --> 15:55.294
was there anyone said that he helped pay his way to 
charlton by milking a cow he he paid his entire

15:55.662 --> 16:22.564
education except for five dollars his mother gave 
him seeing his dad really didn't want him to go to

15:55.662 --> 16:22.564
college because he said see earl had made his own 
money from the time he was seven years old and doing

15:55.662 --> 16:22.564
one thing another selling door-to-door very soon 
and then the time he was going in high school, he was

16:22.882 --> 16:25.004
working in a drug store. And his dad said, I think 
it'd be foolish for you to go to college because

16:26.305 --> 16:37.095
you're making more money now than I was when I 
married your mother. But the coach, the football

16:37.115 --> 16:41.799
coach at Carlton had been through this a little 
time. And his doctor had lunch at a little cafe

16:42.640 --> 16:45.002
there. And he said to the owner, he said, do you have 
any good football players around here? He said,

16:50.828 --> 16:52.129
well, we got one. He said, it's rubber. So he looked 
him up. It didn't take him long to find him. The town

16:57.140 --> 16:58.103
was so tiny. And so I have this and a letter that this 
coach wrote to me three years after my husband's

16:59.667 --> 17:08.008
death. But he told Earl, he said, if you'll come and 
play football, he said, we'll find a way for you to

17:08.512 --> 17:16.262
get through school. Of course, they didn't make, 
they didn't give them anything, you know, for

17:16.282 --> 17:21.489
playing. I said, well, they didn't have the free 
use of the uniform. That was just about it.

17:29.099 --> 17:32.704
He got a job waiting tables in the college dining 
room. And he's still running kind of short of

17:34.126 --> 17:36.089
money. And so he got a job at a drug store that was 
just across the campus. So he was working those two

17:43.499 --> 17:44.921
jobs. And at the end of his first year, he was 
elected captain for the following year. And so the

17:51.731 --> 17:54.955
next fall, he started out with his two jobs. He was 
still having just a rough time. He just didn't

17:57.276 --> 18:01.060
think he could get by on what he was making. So he 
went to see a coach one day right at lunchtime to

18:02.101 --> 18:11.051
tell him that he was going to have to go home, but he 
just couldn't make it. Coach said, oh, Rudder

18:11.071 --> 18:18.139
said, just go on, and I'm getting ready to go to 
Lions Club, and you have to come back after lunch,

18:11.071 --> 18:18.139
and I'll talk to you. So when he got to Lions Club, he 
told the membership, he said, look, we've got to

18:18.159 --> 18:24.486
figure out some way to keep him in school. He said, 
I'm about to lose my captain. And so you just see

18:28.622 --> 18:31.524
what we can do to help him. So they decided to buy a 
Jersey milk cow. And they let him graze it around

18:35.208 --> 18:42.175
the football field and milk it and sell the milk to 
the dining hall. And they still laugh up there and

18:42.195 --> 18:51.564
say that the first day he took his bucket to the 
dining hall to sell it, it wasn't quite full. So

18:52.045 --> 18:54.507
they didn't pay him what he thought he was going to 
get. So the next day when he dealt the cow, he was on

18:55.516 --> 19:00.304
the way to the dining hall with the milk. Just 
happened to notice there was a water faucet. He

19:02.908 --> 19:05.151
said from then on he always drived full bucket. I 
guess that's true. That's a

19:08.757 --> 19:13.584
good story. Okay. So you met General Rutter when he 
was a junior in college? No, you were a junior in

19:18.392 --> 19:20.275
college and he was already a coach? No, I was a 
freshman in college, and he was coaching today.

19:29.384 --> 19:33.893
But his first year out of A&M, times were so tough 
then. And he did all kinds of things to get through

19:35.206 --> 19:37.328
A&M. See, he came down here for his last two years. 
Graduated here in 1932. But he couldn't get a job

19:43.173 --> 19:48.698
except for one with a highway department. They 
were building a road between Eden and Menard. And

19:52.181 --> 19:59.088
he was, his first year out of A&M with his degree, he 
took a job digging ditches for 25 cents an hour. And

20:00.249 --> 20:03.812
then the next fall, he got the job coaching the 
baby. When did we get married? We got married in

20:08.039 --> 20:10.122
1937, see? I had finished Texas in 36, taught that 
one year in Brady. And then we married in 1936. And

20:20.297 --> 20:30.010
in 1941, he got off into the war, 1940? Yeah. We had 
our first child. in Stephenville, in 40. And when

20:35.858 --> 20:43.428
he was just about a year old, maybe a month or two 
after he was a year old, he was called into the

20:35.858 --> 20:43.428
service. Because, see, he got his reserve 
permission when he graduated from A&M. And he was

20:48.595 --> 20:53.622
first sent to Fort St. Houston. And from there to 
infantry school in Fort Benning and then back to

20:53.763 --> 20:59.871
Fort St. Houston. Then to the 83rd Division up in 
Camp Atterbury, Indiana. By then we had a second

21:05.120 --> 21:07.143
child, that was 1942. Were you following him 
along? Oh yeah, until he went overseas.

21:15.053 --> 21:18.498
So anyway, we lived in all kinds of places. People 
would not believe, it would just sound like a crazy

21:18.598 --> 21:26.789
story if I mentioned how we had lived in some of 
those places. But you did what you had to do. And so

21:29.264 --> 21:36.077
he went overseas in November of 1943.

21:38.201 --> 21:46.456
And so when he went overseas, I had to bring the two 
children and come back home. And so we came back to

21:46.476 --> 21:51.846
stay in Brady because his brother and his And back 
in 35, he was responsible for putting in a

21:52.214 --> 22:00.105
drugstore in Brady, which he and his brother all 
played together. And then my parents would be just

22:00.125 --> 22:04.871
36 miles from me. They could be a lot of help and 
worry. So we stayed there during the war. And you

22:15.966 --> 22:16.707
had two children? I had two children. We were in two 
years apart. Well, the first one was a son named

22:22.167 --> 22:29.336
James Earl Rudder, Jr., but they always called him 
Bud. The next one was Anne, the

22:30.517 --> 22:36.465
daughter. So during the war, you and the children 
went back home? Stayed in David, uh-huh. Until he

22:41.191 --> 22:45.296
came

22:41.191 --> 22:45.296
home? Yeah. What about his actions during the war? 
Can you tell me about those? Actually, when he was

22:51.513 --> 23:01.068
in the 83rd Division at Camp Atterbury in Indiana, 
the War Department decided that all divisions

22:51.513 --> 23:01.068
should put in some ranger training. So they put him 
in charge of that. And General Friedendahl went

23:04.233 --> 23:09.842
around the country looking at all the divisions 
and inspecting a program for ranger training, and

23:10.700 --> 23:15.227
he decided that that was the best. And so he named 
Earl to command the second ranger battalion, the

23:16.448 --> 23:23.779
first had been formed, commanded by General 
Darby. And he did not come back from war. He was

23:28.506 --> 23:30.950
killed late in the war. And Earl commanded the 
second ranger battalion, Camp Forest,

23:31.010 --> 23:39.222
Tennessee, trained there, and then took them 
overseas. And they trained in England,

23:39.742 --> 23:45.189
in Cornwall. They had cliffs there. When he found 
out what their mission was, it was really a tough

23:47.492 --> 23:53.820
one. And so they trained in Cornwall, and they 
trained some on the Isle of Wight. And their

24:01.850 --> 24:03.893
mission was to... climb these 100-foot cliffs in 
Normandy, Pointe du Hoc, and knock out the six

24:04.936 --> 24:20.673
155-millimeter guns that the Germans had placed 
there that could fire on Utah and Omaha beaches.

24:21.314 --> 24:23.016
When the soldiers came across. What? When the 
soldiers came across the beaches. Oh, yeah, when

24:25.939 --> 24:28.202
they landed. They were to knock out these guns so 
the soldiers could land on those two beaches.

24:33.218 --> 24:37.065
because his point jutted out right between the two 
beaches. And everybody thought it was sort of a

24:37.085 --> 24:42.735
suicide mission, that there's no way to take a dip. 
And General Bradley, in his book, A Soldier's

24:43.437 --> 24:52.133
Story, describes it as the most difficult 
assignment he ever gave a soldier in his entire

24:43.437 --> 24:52.133
career. And so, for the D-Day mission, Earl was 
given command of not only the 2nd, but the 5th

24:57.299 --> 25:01.767
battalion. He could command both of them for the 
invasion. And so there were only three companies

25:06.335 --> 25:21.602
out of the 2nd that went up the cliffs, D, E, and F. 
And the other companies, A and B, they landed on

25:06.335 --> 25:21.602
other parts of the invasion beaches. And he 
handpicked 225 men for this mission. And at the end

25:28.283 --> 25:32.638
of the first day, there were only 90 able to bear 
arms.

