cliff. But as it happened, when they were loaded 
off the ships that brought them across the channel

26:11.768 --> 26:15.955
into their small landing craft. They were 
assigned a British guide boat. And this British

26:20.623 --> 26:23.368
guide boat took them off course. There was another 
point that looked very similar, but it was about

26:23.388 --> 26:29.999
four miles to the east, at least four miles, maybe 
further. And so it didn't take long for my husband

26:31.101 --> 26:37.472
to realize that they were headed for the wrong 
point. And he kept trying to tell this British

26:38.144 --> 26:43.632
guide boat that they were headed for the wrong 
point, but they ignored it. And finally, he had

26:45.114 --> 27:04.422
just take command of his own little bunch of 
landing craft and turn them to the west toward the

26:45.114 --> 27:04.422
proper point, which meant, see, if they had gone in 
on time, the Germans would have been driven

26:45.114 --> 27:04.422
underground because they had a vast, array of 
underground tunnels. They couldn't stay up on the

27:08.918 --> 27:11.502
top with all the shelling. So if they could have 
been there at the proper time, the Germans would

27:12.865 --> 27:16.892
have been totally surprised. But at the time that 
they were supposed to be there, the shelling quit.

27:22.627 --> 27:26.672
And yet they were far from being there, and the seas 
were very rough. I think the waves were at least six

27:26.812 --> 27:28.895
feet high. And so they had to come along parallel to 
the coastline. And the Germans by then had had

27:35.703 --> 27:43.032
time, they were about 40 minutes late, had had time 
to come out of the underground And so they were on

27:43.012 --> 27:48.541
top of the cliff waiting for them. They were firing 
at them, and they were cutting the ropes that they

27:49.141 --> 27:52.407
were climbing up. See, the way they would get up 
those cliffs, they had grappling hooks attached

27:53.048 --> 28:06.268
to ropes that they would fire by rocket off their 
little landing craft. dig into the soil. I'm not

28:09.392 --> 28:10.414
saying it's very good. And then they'd find these 
ropes, and then they had some rope ladders that

28:12.256 --> 28:16.342
they had. And they also had some, my husband had 
borrowed some ladders from the fire department in

28:17.143 --> 28:26.817
London, and they were in sections. They put those 
together and put up on the face of the cliff. But

28:30.783 --> 28:34.348
anyway, as I say, it was unfortunate that the It 
couldn't have gone off on time, but it was not the

28:34.750 --> 28:39.485
fault of the rangers, it was the fault of the 
Buddhist guide boat. But anyway, they were up

28:41.270 --> 28:48.372
there then, and it denied them their 
reinforcements that they were to have had. If they

28:49.904 --> 29:04.083
didn't get the signal that they were up on the 
cliffs by a certain time, then the rest of the

28:49.904 --> 29:04.083
second and fifth battalions would land on Omaha 
Beach, which they did. And then they'd have to

29:05.064 --> 29:12.013
fight over land to get to the ranges where it 
pointed to Hope. So it was not until two and a half

29:12.770 --> 29:19.007
days later that the reinforcements got to them. By 
then they had run out of ammunition, they'd run out

29:19.468 --> 29:26.506
of food, and they'd had several German 
counterattacks. Of course they were really

29:30.286 --> 29:31.228
outnumbered. And the things looked pretty bleak 
there for a while. Of course, on that day my husband

29:37.660 --> 29:44.533
was shot through the leg, but fortunately it 
didn't hit the bone. And when he established his

29:46.176 --> 29:53.290
command post, he was inside of this open sort of a 
German bunker. And there were two men, one on

29:53.827 --> 30:11.818
either side of him, and a shell came in from, I 
guess, one of the ships out in the channel, hit the

29:53.827 --> 30:11.818
side of this rock bunker, and it killed the men on 
either side of him, and he was... left in the middle

30:13.115 --> 30:40.236
he got shrapnel in his arm and his leg and his hip 
actually that day so they considered he was

30:13.115 --> 30:40.236
wounded three times but he never left command of 
the of the rangers they had one doctor who actually

30:13.115 --> 30:40.236
in civilian life was a pediatrician but he kind of 
patched him up put bandage on and he kept going so

30:13.115 --> 30:40.236
anyway i think uh that of all the challenges that he 
faced throughout his life, that was probably the

30:41.785 --> 30:49.095
worst. And I think since he lived through that, I 
kind of think the challenges that came up later, he

30:50.177 --> 31:03.716
always could do because of having had that 
experience. Do you think that the Lord changed

31:03.736 --> 31:05.018
him? Oh, I do. In fact, he said that war was such a 
terrible thing. And that wasn't the end of it. He

31:14.816 --> 31:19.268
was given command of the 109th Regiment in the 28th 
Division. on the 8th of December, I believe it was,

31:20.598 --> 31:36.740
and on the 16th then, the Germans' last great 
offensive was out of the bush, and it hit right

31:20.598 --> 31:36.740
where his division was. His regiment held the 
southern flank, and parts of the division were

31:37.361 --> 31:45.171
just absolutely all but wiped out. So that was 
another tough experience for him. So there's no

31:49.228 --> 31:52.210
doubt that the war changed him more than anything. 
And so when he came home, he felt so thankful just to

31:53.171 --> 31:57.995
have survived it. But he said, if you didn't want it 
to happen again, you better get to work on the home

31:58.816 --> 32:04.361
front. And so he'd hardly bring it back. He got 
home. And he'd been gone two years. And of course, I

32:11.046 --> 32:15.310
was so glad to get him home. The War Department 
turned around and had him, put him in command of a

32:15.290 --> 32:23.180
Victor Loaning Train that had all sorts of war 
souvenirs. And sent him all around the country

32:24.882 --> 32:28.586
selling war bonds. So that kept him another, oh 
let's see, that was from September until two days

32:28.606 --> 32:37.237
before Christmas. So he got home. And then in April 
he was elected mayor. We were in Brady. And so he

32:44.382 --> 32:52.253
served as mayor for six years, three times. And he 
was elected to the State Democratic Executive

32:52.273 --> 32:55.898
Committee. And while on that, he got three plans 
for the governor. He was Alan Shivers at the time.

33:06.973 --> 33:09.597
And so in 1955, The land commissioner had been, he 
was serving, I think he'd been elected to his ninth

33:10.505 --> 33:17.053
term. He was head of the whole messianic 
organization in the state of Texas. Most

33:24.002 --> 33:24.443
respected person. But he saw an opportunity to 
make some money, but it was crooked. He ended up in

33:27.707 --> 33:28.368
prison. And he could tell what he was being caught 
up with. And so he just said he, for personal

33:33.454 --> 33:39.702
reasons, he wasn't going to serve that term that 
he'd been elected to. So that meant that the

33:39.884 --> 33:43.889
governor had to appoint somebody. So the governor 
appointed Earl as land commissioner. Mitch was

33:48.334 --> 33:51.918
the general land officer for this property. That 
was a big job, and things were in such a glorious

33:51.938 --> 33:55.161
mess.

33:58.125 --> 34:05.453
But he waded into that and straightened it out, ran 
for re-election, got re-elected. And in the

34:05.838 --> 34:23.217
middle of his second term, the board of directors 
that was called in at A&M came and wanted him to come

34:05.838 --> 34:23.217
here as vice president, actually, but with the 
understanding that he was to run this campus. And

34:23.957 --> 34:30.985
then the following year, he was made president of 
A&M. Of course, many, many things happened to

34:31.910 --> 34:38.038
change the face of the university during his 
administration.

34:45.367 --> 34:48.231
What were some of those things that changed 
Hayden? Well, at the beginning of the spring

34:48.251 --> 34:56.702
semester of 1958, the spring he came here, And I'd 
say he left in the middle of his term that he'd been

34:57.526 --> 35:01.817
elected to. We worked very hard to get him 
re-elected at campaign headquarters in our home

35:01.837 --> 35:07.671
in Austin. And, like I say, uh, but when the NM 
wanted to come here, that was it. Uh, at the time we

35:14.109 --> 35:18.896
got here, there were less than 7,000 students. I 
think there'd been a little more than 7,000 in the

35:18.916 --> 35:24.104
fall, the start of the fall semester. But, of 
course, it dropped off a little bit at the start of

35:24.144 --> 35:28.250
the second semester. And it was all male, all 
military. The name was Agricultural Mechanical

35:31.975 --> 35:34.519
College. And integration had not taken place. So 
during his administration, girls were admitted.

35:42.288 --> 35:43.410
That was 1963. The name change took place the same 
year. And they didn't want to give up the A&M part of

35:48.057 --> 35:53.024
the name. See, so many land grant colleges over the 
nation, they took like LSU, Louisiana State. It

36:01.477 --> 36:03.780
was a land grant college. That was a trend. But the 
former students didn't want that. They wanted

36:09.728 --> 36:11.490
that A&M . But it didn't stand for agricultural 
mechanical anymore. So they just decided to call

36:15.254 --> 36:18.657
it Texas A&M University. That was in 63. 
Integration, I'm not sure what year that took

36:21.600 --> 36:24.243
place. But it was done smooth itself. No problem. 
Of course, during the 60s, There was a lot of

36:35.249 --> 36:42.242
student unrest at other schools, but not here, not 
at A&M. That was one thing that, he had been a

36:42.602 --> 36:55.125
student, General Jim Hannigan, that he had gone to 
Washington and looked for somebody that was young

36:42.602 --> 36:55.125
enough and just retired from the Army. And the 
Prima, too, I believe, pretty well kept things

36:56.127 --> 36:59.653
under control. Although there was a group that 
came over here and tried to organize, but they had

37:00.410 --> 37:11.761
that cord so organized against it that they never 
got hold of it. How did they maintain control?

37:17.506 --> 37:20.790
Well, they just had that much discipline. It was so 
much smaller then compared to now. they came over

37:27.781 --> 37:55.392
here i guess in school where i went and tried to 
organize had their literature and all that but

37:27.781 --> 37:55.392
they didn't they didn't get the first place and 
they sent them in from oh i don't know exactly how

37:27.781 --> 37:55.392
far away but trying to organize things like that 
but they just let it be known they weren't going to

37:27.781 --> 37:55.392
stand for it the administration let it be known

37:57.717 --> 38:03.405
In 1965, he was named head of the entire system. So 
he was still president of A&M here, but head of the

38:03.425 --> 38:08.272
whole system. And he just, he never stopped. He 
just worked night and

38:11.396 --> 38:17.725
day. And I say in 19, well, in fact, January of 1970, 
he got sick. died in March, March 23rd, at the age of

38:26.978 --> 38:31.945
59. That's young. Yeah, very

38:32.807 --> 38:37.554
young. I don't know where we go from here. So, you 
were older than he was? He was six years older than I

38:45.806 --> 38:48.450
was. Oh, I'm sorry. I'm sorry. I do know. Okay, 
um... Okay, I thought your... But I never

38:53.658 --> 38:59.047
considered it. I just, you see we had five 
children, and in all these things that he did, I

39:00.249 --> 39:16.577
know when, when the governor poached him about 
being mentioned at the general I told him, I said,

39:17.671 --> 39:24.367
you do what you want to do because my work's cut out 
for me to produce the children. And he had a kind of a

39:24.447 --> 39:25.951
system anyway. He took care of his job and 
business. I took care of the house and the

39:30.783 --> 39:32.226
children. It worked out pretty well. Was he really 
active with the children or things like that?

39:38.877 --> 39:42.704
Well, he was all so busy with his job from the time 
they were seven. Our youngest was only eight

39:44.668 --> 39:50.218
months old when he was made land commissioner. So 
it pretty well fell my lot. Of course, he did, you

39:54.185 --> 39:56.048
know, what he could.

40:04.752 --> 40:10.361
Okay, you once said that Lyndon Johnson had 
offered positions to do no matter? Yeah. Can you

40:10.721 --> 40:11.643
tell me about that? Well, it goes way back. In 1948, 
when Lyndon Johnson ran for the Senate, he asked

40:17.291 --> 40:30.051
Earl, we were living in Brady, he asked Earl to be 
his campaign manager in the district, which had 16

40:17.291 --> 40:30.051
or 18 counties, I've forgotten. We lived close to 
where his opponent lived. He said, now you can't

40:34.099 --> 40:38.585
carry this county because you're too close to 
where Colt Stevenson lived. As it turned out, the

40:40.207 --> 40:47.357
county where we lived went for him by more votes 
than he won the statewide election by. He only won

40:49.019 --> 40:53.345
the election by 87 votes statewide, which is 
unheard of. That's why they call them landslide

40:54.246 --> 40:56.189
limits. And so after that, anything that Earl 
asked of him. He always came through for him. But

41:07.222 --> 41:24.945
when

41:07.222 --> 41:24.945
I'm looking at the picture of Lyndon Johnson over 
there, which reminds me of when we got it, they had

41:07.222 --> 41:24.945
asked us up to the White House in 66 to a dinner for 
Henry Cabot Lodge. and, uh, flight experience for

41:25.904 --> 41:31.831
me earlier than the floor that I had. And, uh, so the 
next morning after the... We stayed there in the

41:31.851 --> 41:40.602
White House up on the third floor, and the 
President's quarters were on the second floor.

41:41.763 --> 41:46.149
And, uh, so we hadn't really had much of a chance to 
visit personally with him. And the next morning,

41:47.510 --> 41:55.540
we were gonna leave fairly soon, and, uh, the 
President called and said to come down to the...

41:55.520 --> 42:08.376
floor below, and I don't know if I should tell this 
or not, he was still in bed in his pajamas and his

41:55.520 --> 42:08.376
hair wasn't combed, he had newspapers scattered 
all around him, and had three TV screens going. He

42:08.777 --> 42:21.713
was talking to Senator Snyder, and as we walked in, 
he said, you know, Senator, I can get nearly

42:08.777 --> 42:21.713
everybody to do what I ask them to do except Earl 
Rudder, and he won't do a blank thing. Because he

42:21.693 --> 42:27.080
had offered, I can't tell you which things he had 
offered Earl. Some in Washington and some were

42:27.461 --> 42:29.623
foreign opponents. But Earl would always say, I'm 
sorry Mr. President, but I have brought too many

42:30.505 --> 42:37.954
good people to A&M to go off and leave. Go off and 
leave. So he wouldn't leave here. And I guess it

42:41.780 --> 42:45.945
wasn't the easiest thing in the world to turn a 
president down, especially one like William

42:41.780 --> 42:45.945
Johnson. Some of the things he brought at A&M, um, 
women were allowed in. Yeah. Coral was made

42:52.590 --> 42:54.171
optional. Coral was made optional. Uh-huh. The 
name was changed, and there was a tremendous

42:55.272 --> 42:59.536
population boom. Well, uh, it boomed...

42:59.556 --> 43:05.943
more so after his death. There's all these things 
that had been keeping it from going. It was about

43:09.186 --> 43:13.990
14,000-something at the time he died, which was 
double what it was when he came here. But, uh...

43:17.195 --> 43:24.051
It's like the lady said last night at this dinner 
for retiring professors. Said he's the one that

43:24.071 --> 43:31.969
made the decision to let it go like that. And of 
course, I think that's true. What did he think

43:34.863 --> 43:38.208
about allowing women to go to A&M? Well, he was for 
it, you see. But the strange thing was, the student

43:39.711 --> 43:44.057
body, all male, was not. They wanted it just like it 
was. And especially these old eggs that were

43:46.501 --> 43:49.806
already out of A&M. Some of them never did get over 
it. They thought things had just gone to pop.

43:54.994 --> 43:58.660
Because they wanted to be just like it was when they 
were students here. But actually, the student

43:59.602 --> 44:06.851
body, when he got up before them and told them they 
were going to admit the girls, they booed him. They

44:07.712 --> 44:12.057
also burned him in effigy out in front of the house. 
Didn't they also burn the dog in effigy? No. They

44:14.460 --> 44:16.202
didn't burn the dog. They just painted the dog. 
They were always painting that funny bulldog that

44:19.066 --> 44:22.250
he named Ranger. But when the matter of admitting 
the coeds came up, This dog just waddled around all

44:29.082 --> 44:31.387
over campus. Everybody that was in school knew and 
remembered him. But they painted him with a sign

44:34.212 --> 44:37.199
that says, Maggie's Go Home. So they called the 
girls Maggie instead of Abby. And they booed them

44:43.207 --> 44:45.110
outside the house? How long did they do that? Well, 
no, it was at, I guess, G. Raleigh, they had this

44:47.213 --> 44:51.219
meeting. And so we told the student body they were 
going to put the girls in their booty. And then,

44:55.546 --> 45:02.456
see, that was before the old house burned, the one 
that had first been occupied by Lawrence Sullivan

44:55.546 --> 45:02.456
Ross. Built in 1892, and it was in January of 63 that 
it burned from a faulted chimney on one of the

45:03.137 --> 45:12.471
coldest days of the year. And, uh, anyway, uh,

45:13.767 --> 45:23.761
I forgot what I was talking about. Uh, them doing an 
effigy. Oh, burning an effigy out in front of their

45:25.243 --> 45:29.288
house. Up in a tree I looked at at, oh, early morning 
hours, and there was a fire, and I thought, what in

45:29.308 --> 45:35.557
the world? That's what it was. What did he say about 
that? Who, Earl? He didn't say much. I guess he

45:41.806 --> 45:43.588
thought it was kind of funny, I don't know. He was 
not an excitable person. I was one that was

45:46.792 --> 45:50.438
excitable. He was pretty calm. Oh, very calm. And 
about the war, I think you asked me, he didn't

45:52.240 --> 45:58.069
really talk about it. I learned more from other 
people that were in the war with him than I ever

45:58.089 --> 46:03.096
learned from him. Did he have any memories that he 
shared? No, not really. Of course, he was invited

46:07.149 --> 46:09.211
back. It was his regiment that liberated the last 
German stronghold in France, which was Comarch.

46:14.956 --> 46:18.339
It's right on the eastern border. And so right 
after he took office in Austin in 1955, the land

46:18.359 --> 46:32.591
office, General Eisenhower was present, and he 
asked him to be his representative to go to the 10th

46:18.359 --> 46:32.591
anniversary of the liberation of Comarch. So that 
was his first trip back. And then, uh, in 1954,

46:35.813 --> 46:51.289
Collier's Magazine wanted to do an article

46:35.813 --> 46:51.289
on a man that took his son back, and so they chose 
Earl. And, uh, this fellow that was the, uh,

46:52.310 --> 47:00.679
writer, he said he went to Washington to research 
it, and Earl was the ideal one. And, uh, so, That was

47:04.467 --> 47:05.433
unfictical. He went back. But he hesitated about 
going back. He wasn't sure that he really wanted to

47:09.035 --> 47:10.765
go.

